          "body": "The lament David composes — the Song of the Bow — is one of the finest examples of Hebrew qinah poetry outside the Psalter and Lamentations. The qinah meter (a falling 3+2 beat pattern) is built into the Hebrew lines, giving the poem a rhythmic sense of incompletion, of something cut short. The poem is structured by the refrain 'How have the mighty fallen' (ekh naphal gibborim, vv.19, 25, 27) — three movements of grief like three hammer blows. The first movement (vv.19-21) mourns Israel's glory; the second (vv.22-24) honors both Saul and Jonathan as warriors; the third (vv.25-27) narrows to the personal grief for Jonathan. That David commands the sons of Judah to learn this poem (v.18) — including Saul's praise — is an act of political and theological courage. He will not allow corporate grief to be privatized, nor will he permit his own tribe to celebrate Saul's death as a political convenience."
